<failure_categories>
  <category>
    <failure_category>runner_system_failure</failure_category>
    <description>The GitLab Runner itself crashed or failed before the job script ran. Includes "runner system failure" messages, Docker daemon errors, container start failures, stuck runners. Transient — retrying resolves these.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>environment_failure</failure_category>
    <description>The job environment could not be provisioned. Includes Docker image pull failures, service container startup errors (postgres, redis), Docker Hub rate limits ("toomanyrequests"). Transient — retrying resolves these.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>network_failure</failure_category>
    <description>Network connectivity failed during job execution. Includes DNS resolution errors ("could not resolve host"), connection refused/reset, TLS handshake failures, HTTP 502/503/504 from external services, artifact download timeouts. Transient — retrying resolves these.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>permissions_failure</failure_category>
    <description>Authentication or authorization errors requiring human intervention. Includes "access denied", 403/401 errors, expired CI tokens, SSH key failures, protected environment blocks, insufficient bridge permissions. Persistent — retrying will not help.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>resource_limit_failure</failure_category>
    <description>The job exceeded a system resource limit. Includes OOM killed, "no space left on device", job timeout ("exceeded the time limit"), disk quota exceeded. Transient — typically caused by system contention.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>ci_config_error</failure_category>
    <description>The CI/CD configuration is invalid. Includes .gitlab-ci.yml syntax errors, invalid job/stage references, undefined CI variables, incorrect `rules:` clauses, missing `needs:` dependencies. The job script may not have run at all.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>test_failure</failure_category>
    <description>
      A test assertion failed due to a defect in the code. Includes assertion errors, expected-vs-actual mismatches.
      {% if merge_request_url %}
      Use this only when there is a clear causal link — the failing test imports or exercises code that was changed.
      Use `flaky_test` instead when the failure has no link to changed files or also exists on the target branch.
      {% else %}
      Use this when the test failure is caused by a code defect that can be fixed.
      Use `flaky_test` instead when the failure is purely intermittent or timing-dependent.
      {% endif %}
    </description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>flaky_test</failure_category>
    <description>
      A test failure that is intermittent such as passes on retry, timing-dependent, race conditions, random ordering sensitivity
      {% if merge_request_url %}
      , and pre-existing failures on the target branch ("master-broken specs").
      {% else %}

      IMPORTANT: When the pipeline ran against the default branch, a flaky test here is usually a defect in the test itself
      (race condition, ordering dependence, timing assumption) that a code or configuration change can fix
      — including de-flaking or quarantining it.
      When such a fix exists, set `suggested_fix_type` to `code_fix` and `decision` to `create_plan` rather than `no_action`;
      retrying only masks it. Only fall back to `retry_job`/`no_action` if the intermittency has no code-level fix
      (i.e. it is really an infrastructure or network issue, which belongs in those categories).
      {% endif %}
    </description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>lint_failure</failure_category>
    <description>A linter, formatter, or static analysis tool reported violations. Includes ESLint, RuboCop, Prettier, semgrep, pajamas-adoption-scanner output. The specific rule or violation must be visible in the job trace — do not infer from the MR diff or branch name.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>build_failure</failure_category>
    <description>The project failed to compile or build. Includes compilation errors, syntax errors in source code, type errors, bad import statements. Use `dependency_failure` instead when the root cause is a missing or incompatible package.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>dependency_failure</failure_category>
    <description>Package installation or resolution failed. Includes "package not found", version conflicts, `bundle install` / `yarn install` / `pip install` errors, lockfile conflicts. The failure occurs during dependency installation, not during source code compilation.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>insufficient_context</failure_category>
    <description>The job logs are missing, truncated, or insufficient to classify the failure. Also use this when a scanner name is visible but the specific rule that fired is not in the trace.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>security_sensitive</failure_category>
    <description>The failure involves security scanning findings requiring human review. Includes secret detection alerts, SAST (Brakeman, Bandit), DAST findings, dependency vulnerability scans, license compliance failures.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>no_failing_jobs_detected</failure_category>
    <description>No failing jobs were found in the pipeline or any of its downstream pipelines after traversal. The pipeline metadata was retrieved successfully but reported no failed jobs to analyze. Use this rather than `insufficient_context`, which applies when failing jobs exist but their logs are missing or truncated.</description>
  </category>
  <category>
    <failure_category>unknown_failure</failure_category>
    <description>The failure does not fit any other category after reviewing the full job trace. Use as a last resort. Prefer `insufficient_context` when the issue is lack of log data rather than an unrecognizable pattern.</description>
  </category>
</failure_categories>
